04594nam a22006015i 9789633864999DE-B159720220729113935.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220729t20221998hu     fo  d z      eng d  a9789633864999  a(DE-B1597)633250  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahucHU 7aPSY0260002bisacsh04a361.11 aBar-On, Dan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Indescribable and the Undiscussable :bReconstructing Human Discourse after Trauma /cDan Bar-On. 1aBudapest ;aNew York : bCentral European University Press, c[2022] 4cÂ©1998  a1 online resource (326 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgments -- tContents -- tPrologue -- tIntroduction -- tPart I. The indescribable: "soft" impediments to discourse -- t1. Multiple representations: maps of mind and nature -- t2 Subjective theories of cardiac patients -- t3. Negotiating attributions: developing a constructive dialog -- t4. Feeling-facts: searching for words related to feelings -- tInterlude -- t5. Pure and impure ideologies: the change of social contexts -- tPart II. Severe impediments to discourse -- tIntroduction -- t6. Silenced facts from the victimizers' perspective -- t7. Silenced facts from the victims' perspective -- t8. My father and I: constructing a mora! imagination -- t9. Psychosocial learning from experience -- tEpilogue -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPeople--laymen and practitioners alike--face serious difficulties in making sense of each other's feelings, behavior, and discourse in everyday life and after traumatic experiences. Acknowledging and working through these difficulties is the subject of this extremely interesting and highly readable book. After a critical look at the psychological and philosophical literature, Dan Bar-On identifies two groups of impediments. First, the indescribable, as it appears when individuals try to understand and integrate their first heart attack into their previous life-experience, when a group of pathfinders talk about their different maps of the mind and nature, or when a team of welfare practitioners tries to develop a common approach to their regional population. Second, the undiscussable, as it appears in the transmission, from generation to generation, of the traumatic experiences of the families of both Holocaust survivors and Nazi perpetrators, the book showing how their descendants can work through the burden of the past by confronting themselves and each other through a prolonged group encounter. This book provides a unique way of looking at life experiences, individual as well as inter-personal. It proposes a new psychological theoretical framework in a way to which both laymen and professionals can relate while confronting similar issues in their everyday experiences and discourse. The book is of especial relevance to present-day Central and East European societies, relating as it does to the problems of psychological adaptation arising from the transition from totalitarian to democratic regimes.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 7aPSYCHOLOGY / Movements / Psychoanalysis.2bisacsh  aPsychiatry, Psychology, Traumas.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCentral European University Press eBook-Package 2013-1998z978311078055040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789633864999423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9789633864999/original  a978-3-11-078055-0  Central European University Press eBook-Package 2013-1998c1998d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE